# =============================================================================
# GDPR API smoke-test playbook
# =============================================================================
#
# Pre-requisites:
#   1. The `gdpr-local` Spring profile is active on the backend. See
#      `README.md` → "Enabling the GDPR subsystem locally (`gdpr-local` profile)".
#      Without it, the admin endpoints exist but the cascade is a no-op and
#      the inactivity cron doesn't tick.
#   2. Keycloak is running with `keycloak/realm-export.json` imported — this
#      provisions `testuser`, `adminuser`, the `gdpr-admin` realm role, and
#      the `expenses-frontend` public client used by the SPA.
#   3. The SPA is reachable at http://localhost:3000 (Docker stack) or
#      http://localhost:5173 (`npm run dev`) so you can log in there and copy
#      tokens from the browser. See "How auth works" below.
#
# How auth works:
#   Every request below sends `Authorization: Bearer {{UserToken}}` (or
#   `{{AdminToken}}`). Both env vars start empty in `http-client.env.json` —
#   you populate them by copy-pasting tokens minted by the SPA's auth-code
#   flow, because that's the only flow Keycloak attaches an `auth_time` claim
#   to. `FreshAuthenticationService.requireFresh()` rejects tokens without
#   `auth_time`, so destructive endpoints would otherwise 401 with
#   `insufficient_user_authentication`.
#
#   Workflow per token:
#     1. Open the SPA: http://localhost:3000 (or :5173 with the Vite dev
#        server). Log in as `testuser` (password `password`) — the SPA uses
#        keycloak-js's auth-code flow, so the resulting JWT has `auth_time`.
#     2. Open browser DevTools → Network tab → click any `/api/...` request
#        → Headers → copy the value after `Bearer ` in `Authorization`.
#        Faster alternative: DevTools Console → `await keycloak.token` if the
#        SPA exposes the instance globally (it does in dev mode).
#     3. Paste into `local.UserToken` in `http-client.env.json` and save.
#     4. Log out, log in as `adminuser` (password `adminpassword`), repeat
#        the copy into `local.AdminToken`.
#     5. Re-do whichever side hits a 401 (~5 min access-token TTL).
#
#   DO NOT commit the populated env file — the tokens are local secrets.
#
# Run order for a clean smoke test (clicking individual gutter buttons):
#   1. Get my restriction          (expect 204)
#   2. Restrict myself             (expect 201)
#   3. Get my restriction          (expect 200 with body)
#   4. Lift my restriction         (1st call → 202 with liftAvailableAt)
#   5. [wait `restriction.lift-dwell`, default 30s in gdpr-local]
#   6. Lift my restriction         (2nd call → 204)
#   7. Admin: restrict user        (expect 201)
#   8. Admin: lift restriction     (1st → 202, 2nd → 204 after dwell)
#   9. Admin: erase user           (terminal — `testuser` is gone)
#        → recover with `docker compose down -v && docker compose up -d`
#        → then log into the SPA as `testuser` again and re-copy the token.
#
# The admin section targets testuser via `{{UserSub}}`, a fixture UUID
# pinned in `keycloak/realm-export.json` (id `00000000-…-0000000000a`).
# That UUID is the testuser's Keycloak `sub` claim — it has to match the
# value of `local.UserSub` in `http-client.env.json` for the admin paths
# above to resolve to the same user the testuser JWT represents. `adminuser`
# has no pinned `id` because nothing references it by UUID.
# =============================================================================


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Section 1 — Subject-facing endpoints (`/api/users/me/...`)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# All scoped to the caller's own JWT subject — no `userId` path variable.
# No role required beyond ordinary authentication; destructive ops require
# fresh `auth_time`.

### GET my current restriction state
# Art. 15 over the restriction record itself.
# Returns 204 when no restriction is in place, 200 with the [RestrictionDto]
# otherwise.
GET {{ExpensesApiUrl}}/api/users/me/restriction
Authorization: Bearer {{UserToken}}
Accept: application/json

### Restrict my own processing
# Art. 18 — request restriction.
# Valid `ground` values: ACCURACY_CONTESTED | UNLAWFUL_NOT_ERASED |
#                       CONTROLLER_NO_LONGER_NEEDS | OBJECTION_PENDING
# `reasonNote` is optional on the subject path (max 1000 chars).
# Returns 201 with the [RestrictionDto].
POST {{ExpensesApiUrl}}/api/users/me/restrict
Authorization: Bearer {{UserToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "ground": "ACCURACY_CONTESTED",
  "reasonNote": "Disputing the imported expense amounts from CSV"
}

### Lift my restriction — STEP 1 (sends the Art. 18(3) pre-lift notice)
# First call: returns 202 with `liftNoticeSentAt` + `liftAvailableAt`.
# The dwell between the two calls is the `restriction.lift-dwell` value
# from the active profile (default `PT30S` in `gdpr-local`).
DELETE {{ExpensesApiUrl}}/api/users/me/restrict
Authorization: Bearer {{UserToken}}
Accept: application/json

### Lift my restriction — STEP 2 (after dwell — performs the actual lift)
# Wait at least `restriction.lift-dwell` after the first call. Returns 204.
# Calling this before the dwell elapses returns 202 again (notice already sent).
# Calling it with no live restriction returns 204 (NothingToLift).
DELETE {{ExpensesApiUrl}}/api/users/me/restrict
Authorization: Bearer {{UserToken}}
Accept: application/json

### DESTRUCTIVE — erase my own account (Art. 17)
# Returns 200 with the cascade summary (`ErasureResultDto`) including the
# `followUpInstructions` list (browser localStorage, mobile sync file, etc.).
# After this call, `testuser` is gone from BOTH the projection tables AND the
# Keycloak realm. To get it back: `docker compose down -v && docker compose up -d`
# (wipes the volume → realm re-import re-provisions both users).
DELETE {{ExpensesApiUrl}}/api/users/me
Authorization: Bearer {{UserToken}}
Accept: application/json


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Section 2 — Operator endpoints (`/api/admin/users/{userId}/...`)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Requires the `gdpr-admin` realm role (provisioned on `adminuser` by the
# realm export). All paths take a `{userId}` — we use `{{UserSub}}` from
# `http-client.env.json`, which mirrors testuser's pinned realm-export id.

### Admin: get another user's restriction state
GET {{ExpensesApiUrl}}/api/admin/users/{{UserSub}}/restriction
Authorization: Bearer {{AdminToken}}
Accept: application/json

### Admin-applied restriction
# Unlike the subject path, `reasonNote` is REQUIRED here (NotBlank,
# max 1000 chars) — an operator-applied restriction should always
# record the operator's justification (court order ref, fraud
# investigation, etc.).
POST {{ExpensesApiUrl}}/api/admin/users/{{UserSub}}/restrict
Authorization: Bearer {{AdminToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "ground": "UNLAWFUL_NOT_ERASED",
  "reasonNote": "Court order 2026-CV-0481 — preserve pending discovery"
}

### Admin: lift a user's restriction — STEP 1 (pre-lift notice)
DELETE {{ExpensesApiUrl}}/api/admin/users/{{UserSub}}/restrict
Authorization: Bearer {{AdminToken}}
Accept: application/json

### Admin: lift a user's restriction — STEP 2 (after dwell — actual lift)
DELETE {{ExpensesApiUrl}}/api/admin/users/{{UserSub}}/restrict
Authorization: Bearer {{AdminToken}}
Accept: application/json

### DESTRUCTIVE — admin-driven erasure
# `reasonNote` is REQUIRED on the admin path (NotBlank, max 1000 chars) so
# the audit row records *why* an operator reached past the user's
# self-service erasure. The cascade is the same as the subject path:
# projections wiped, audit hash recorded, Keycloak account deleted (when
# `gdpr-local` is active). The admin's subject is recorded as `actor_id`
# (hashed) — the data subject's identifier is NOT retained.
DELETE {{ExpensesApiUrl}}/api/admin/users/{{UserSub}}
Authorization: Bearer {{AdminToken}}
Content-Type: application/json
Accept: application/json

{
  "reasonNote": "Subject submitted notarised erasure request via postal mail 2026-06-01"
}
